{'id': 101, 'date': '2026-11-01', 'day': 'Sunday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Surgery Before Summer — Plan Your Joint Replacement Now', 'caption': "Summer is almost here — and for many people, this season is a reminder of everything hip or knee pain is stopping them from doing. 🌞\n\nThe good news: if you act now, you could be recovered and active well before the heat of December and January arrives.\n\nHere's the rough maths:\n- Book a consultation → usually within 1–3 weeks\n- Decision to proceed → surgery often scheduled 4–8 weeks out\n- Recovery to walking freely → 6–12 weeks for most patients\n\nThat means someone booking a consultation *this week* could be walking the beach, tending the garden, or enjoying a backyard Christmas gathering — pain-free — by late December or January.\n\nJoint replacement isn't something to rush. But it's also not something to keep putting off.\n\nIf you've been told you need a hip or knee replacement, or you're wondering whether surgery is right for you, now is a great time to have that conversation.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #JointReplacement #SummerReady #HipReplacementAdelaide #KneeReplacementAdelaide #Orthopaedics360 #PainFreeLife #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-01-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Sun-drenched Australian backyard garden with a timber deck, lush green lawn, flowering plants, outdoor furniture, warm golden afternoon light, no people, lifestyle summer photography'},

{'id': 102, 'date': '2026-11-02', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'The Younger Arthroplasty Patient — Activity-Based Implant Selection', 'caption': 'The younger arthroplasty patient: a distinct counselling and implant selection challenge.\n\nThe AOANJRR continues to document a sustained trend: arthroplasty in patients under 65 is increasing sharply, up 188% for TKA and 142% for THA since 2010. These patients present with different expectations, biomechanical demands, and revision risk profiles than the traditional cohort.\n\nKey considerations in this group:\n\n1. Implant longevity and revision burden\nYounger patients will almost certainly outlive their first implant. This should be communicated clearly and early. The goal is not to avoid surgery indefinitely — deconditioning and muscle loss while waiting carry their own costs — but to time it optimally and select an implant strategy that preserves future revision options.\n\n2. Bearing surface selection\nIn active patients under 60, I favour ceramic-on-highly-cross-linked-polyethylene (CoXLPE). Ceramic femoral heads significantly reduce the risk of third-body wear from ceramic fracture debris compared with alumina-only heads, and XLPE has dramatically reduced liner wear rates compared with conventional poly. Metal-on-metal is not indicated in primary THA.\n\n3. Fixation\nUncemented fixation is generally preferred in this cohort given superior bone quality and the expectation of long implant survival requiring future component exchange.\n\n4. Activity counselling\nHigh-impact activities remain a subject of discussion. Evidence supports return to cycling, swimming, golf, and low-impact aerobic exercise. High-impact running, contact sports, and heavy manual labour carry theoretical — though not well-quantified — risks to long-term implant survival.\n\n5. Psychological and occupational factors\nReturn to work, recreational identity, and expectations around sport and activity should be explored pre-operatively. Patients who feel their goals are understood report higher satisfaction irrespective of functional outcome scores.\n\nThe younger arthroplasty patient is not a contraindication — they are a more demanding clinical conversation.\n\n#Arthroplasty #TotalHipReplacement #TotalKneeReplacement #YoungerPatients #AOANJRR #ImplantSelection #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/the-hip-prosthesis-i-use-for-total-hip-replacements/', 'image_file': '2026-11-02-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Modern private hospital consultation room, ergonomic desk and chairs, anatomy model on shelf, warm afternoon light through frosted window, no people, architectural interior photography'},

{'id': 103, 'date': '2026-11-03', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Knee Replacement Recovery in Summer — Heat, Swelling, and Activity', 'caption': "Recovering from a knee replacement in summer? Here's what to expect — and how to work with the season, not against it. ☀️\n\n🌡️ Heat and swelling\nSome extra swelling in the heat is completely normal. Your knee is healing and blood flow to the area is increased. Keep the leg elevated when resting, stay well hydrated, and use ice packs wrapped in a cloth (not directly on skin) for 15–20 minutes a few times a day.\n\n🏊 Pool and hydrotherapy\nOnce your wound is fully healed (usually around 6 weeks), swimming and hydrotherapy are excellent. The buoyancy reduces load on the joint while allowing full movement. Many patients find summer recovery actually beneficial for this reason.\n\n🚶 Walking\nAdelaide summers can be hot — try to walk in the cooler parts of the day (early morning or evening) rather than midday. Shaded paths and shopping centres work well.\n\n❄️ Air conditioning\nIf you have good air conditioning at home, summer recovery can be comfortable. A cool, consistent indoor environment actually helps with sleep and swelling management.\n\n🌿 What to watch for\nIncreased redness, warmth beyond what's expected, or swelling that doesn't settle with elevation and rest — always contact your surgical team if you're unsure.\n\nRecovery is individual. Your team will give you guidance specific to your surgery and situation.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#KneeReplacement #KneeReplacementAdelaide #KneeReplacement Recovery #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #SummerRecovery #Orthopaedics360 #JointReplacement #KneeHealth #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/knee-replacement-recovery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-03-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Bright airy sunroom with comfortable recliner chair, cool blue cushions, potted indoor plants, light streaming through sheer curtains, no people, warm and calm home recovery setting'},

{'id': 104, 'date': '2026-11-03', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Planning Your Joint Replacement — How Far Ahead Should You Book?', 'caption': "If you're thinking about a hip or knee replacement, one of the most common questions is: how far in advance do I need to plan?\n\nHere's a realistic guide:\n\n📋 Consultation: Most new patients are seen within 1–3 weeks of referral.\n\n🗓️ From consultation to surgery: Once you decide to proceed, surgery is usually scheduled 4–8 weeks out depending on hospital availability and your fitness for surgery.\n\n🩺 Pre-operative workup: You'll need blood tests, a cardiac clearance (if relevant), and a pre-admission appointment — these are arranged for you and typically happen in the 2–4 weeks before surgery.\n\n🏠 Planning your home: Organising home modifications and a support person can take a few weeks, so starting this early reduces stress.\n\n🌅 The takeaway: If you're hoping to have surgery done before Christmas, or want to be active in the new year, now is the ideal time to book a consultation.\n\nDon't wait until you're in crisis — the best results come from planned, prepared surgery.\n\n📞 To arrange a referral, speak to your GP and ask to be referred to Dr Chien-Wen Liew at Orthopaedics 360, Eastwood Private Hospital.\n\n🌐 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\nThis post contains general educational information only. Please consult your GP or specialist for advice tailored to your situation.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedics #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacementAdelaide #KneeReplacementAdelaide', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-03-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Open day-planner diary on a timber desk with a pen and a cup of coffee, warm natural light, no people, flat lay lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 105, 'date': '2026-11-05', 'day': 'Thursday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Carousel', 'topic': '5 Reasons to Act Now Rather Than Wait', 'caption': 'Waiting might feel like the safe option. But when it comes to joint replacement, delay has real costs. Here are 5 reasons to act now rather than keep putting it off. 👇\n\nSwipe through to see each one.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.', 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Osteoarthritis #ChronicPain #Orthopaedics360 #ActNow #JointHealth #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-05-instagram-slide1.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "SLIDE 1 — COVER: Deep navy background, bold white text '5 Reasons to Act Now Rather Than Wait', light blue rule, wordmark '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left. |SLIDE| SLIDE 2 — '1. Pain gets worse over time' — navy panel, body: 'Osteoarthritis is progressive. Bone-on-bone wear doesn't reverse. The longer you wait, the more pain — and the harder the recovery.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 3 — '2. Muscles weaken while you wait' — navy panel, body: 'Reduced activity leads to muscle atrophy. Stronger muscles before surgery mean faster recovery and better outcomes.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 4 — '3. Mental health takes a toll' — navy panel, body: 'Chronic pain affects sleep, mood, and social life. Patients consistently report that surgery restored not just movement — but their sense of self.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 5 — '4. Deconditioning raises surgical risk' — navy panel, body: 'The longer you delay, the less fit you may be for surgery. Early intervention while you are reasonably active is safer.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 6 — '5. Life is happening now' — navy panel, body: 'Every summer, every family occasion, every walk you miss is time you don't get back. Surgery can give those moments back.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 7 — CLOSING: Navy background, 'Ready to talk?' bold white, 'Book a consultation with Dr Chien-Wen Liew', 'drchienwenliew.com.au', wordmark '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left."},

{'id': 106, 'date': '2026-11-06', 'day': 'Friday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Bearing Surface Selection in THA — Current Evidence for Active Patients', 'caption': "Bearing surface selection in THA: what the current evidence says for active and younger patients.\n\nThis is one of the most nuanced decisions in primary THA, and one I'm frequently asked about by colleagues.\n\nThe options\n\n1. Ceramic-on-highly-cross-linked-polyethylene (CoXLPE)\nCurrently the most widely used bearing in primary THA globally and in my own practice. XLPE has dramatically reduced volumetric wear rates compared with conventional polyethylene — by an order of magnitude in retrieval studies. Ceramic femoral heads reduce adhesive and abrasive wear on the liner and eliminate the risk of metallic ion release. Long-term registry data (AOANJRR, NJR) show consistently low revision rates. This is my default bearing for the majority of primary cases.\n\n2. Ceramic-on-ceramic (CoC)\nThe theoretical advantage is the lowest measurable wear rate of any bearing combination. In practice, the differences from CoXLPE are clinically insignificant in most patients given current XLPE quality. CoC bears the risks of ceramic fracture (rare but catastrophic) and audible squeaking (reported in 1–3% of cases at 10 years). I reserve CoC for specific circumstances: very young patients, very high activity demands, and those who raise explicit concern about polyethylene.\n\n3. Metal-on-metal (MoM)\nNo role in primary THA. Well-documented adverse local tissue reactions, pseudotumour formation, and elevated serum metal ions. Abandoned as a primary bearing surface.\n\n4. Metal-on-polyethylene (MoP)\nLargely superseded by ceramic heads given the superior wear profile and absence of metallic ion concerns. Not my current practice in primary THA.\n\nClinical takeaway\nFor the active patient under 65, CoXLPE remains the evidence-based choice. CoC is a reasonable alternative in very young, very active patients after informed discussion of the squeaking risk. The implant brand and bearing surface are secondary to correct surgical technique and implant positioning.\n\nHappy to discuss with GP colleagues or registrars.\n\n#TotalHipReplacement #BearingSurface #THA #Arthroplasty #ImplantSelection #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #AOANJRR #Orthopaedics360", 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/the-hip-prosthesis-i-use-for-total-hip-replacements/', 'image_file': '2026-11-06-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Three orthopaedic hip bearing components — ceramic head, acetabular shell, and poly liner — arranged on a dark reflective surface, dramatic raking studio light, medical product photography, no people'},

{'id': 107, 'date': '2026-11-08', 'day': 'Sunday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Hip Replacement and Water Activities — Pool, Beach, Ocean Swimming', 'caption': "Can you swim after a hip replacement? 🏊 Short answer: yes — and it's one of the best things you can do. Here's what to know.\n\n🏊 Pool swimming\nOnce your wound is fully healed — typically around 6 weeks post-op — swimming is generally permitted and actively encouraged. The water supports your body weight, reduces load on the joint, and allows a good range of hip motion. Many surgeons and physios consider swimming one of the best long-term exercises after hip replacement.\n\n🌊 Ocean and beach swimming\nSame timeline as pool swimming — once the wound is closed and healed. The main consideration at the beach is uneven terrain (sand, rocks, waves) which requires some confidence with walking first. Most patients are cleared for beach swimming from around 3 months, once balance and confidence are established.\n\n🛁 Hydrotherapy\nWarm water hydrotherapy from around 4–6 weeks (once wounds are healed) is a common part of early recovery and is excellent for range of motion and gentle strengthening.\n\n⚠️ What to avoid early\nDon't enter pools, the ocean, or hot tubs until your wound is completely sealed — any open area, scab, or moisture retention risk increases infection risk.\n\n💬 Always confirm the green light with your own surgical team before getting in the water — every patient and wound is different.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#HipReplacement #HipReplacementAdelaide #SwimmingAfterSurgery #JointReplacement #LifeAfterHipReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #HipHealth #DrChienWenLiew #ActiveRecovery', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/swimming-after-hip-replacement/', 'image_file': '2026-11-08-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Calm blue outdoor swimming pool with lane ropes, dappled morning light on the water surface, surrounded by lush greenery, no people, fresh lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 108, 'date': '2026-11-09', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Pre-Surgical Frailty Assessment — CPAX and the 4-Metre Walk Test', 'caption': 'Pre-surgical frailty assessment in arthroplasty: why it matters and what I use in practice.\n\nThe orthopaedic literature has increasingly recognised frailty — distinct from chronological age — as a significant predictor of peri-operative complication, extended length of stay, and 90-day readmission after TJR.\n\nThe challenge for the arthroplasty surgeon is that standard pre-operative workup (ECG, bloods, echo if indicated) may not capture functional reserve adequately.\n\nTwo tools I find clinically useful:\n\n1. The 4-Metre Walk Test (4MWT)\nA simple, reproducible measure of gait speed. A speed below 0.8 m/s is associated with significantly elevated peri-operative risk in older adults undergoing elective surgery. It can be performed in a consultation room in under two minutes. Patients in this category prompt a more thorough pre-operative optimisation discussion — and often a geriatric medicine or anaesthetic pre-assessment.\n\n2. CPAX (Chelsea Critical Care Physical Assessment Tool)\nOriginally developed in ICU rehabilitation, CPAX has utility in assessing functional status across multiple domains: respiratory function, cough, moving in bed, supine to sitting, dynamic sitting balance, standing balance, sit-to-stand, marching on spot, stepping, and transfers. It stratifies patients more broadly than a single gait speed measure.\n\nHow this changes management:\nPatients identified as frail or pre-frail are referred for prehabilitation — supervised physiotherapy, nutritional review (protein and caloric adequacy), and sleep optimisation — prior to scheduling surgery. In some cases I delay the procedure to allow functional improvement.\n\nThe evidence suggests that prehabilitation in frail patients can shift them from high-risk to moderate-risk, with measurable improvements in post-operative functional recovery.\n\nGPs play a critical role here: a brief functional screen at the time of referral — "how far can they walk? are they falling?" — is enormously helpful information.\n\n#FrailtyAssessment #Prehabilitation #TJR #Arthroplasty #PerioperativeMedicine #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #GeriatricMedicine', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-09-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Bright physiotherapy gym with parallel bars, exercise equipment, rubber floor matting, natural light from tall windows, no people, clean modern rehabilitation space'},

{'id': 109, 'date': '2026-11-10', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Quote Card', 'topic': "Quote Card — My Only Regret Is I Didn't Do It Sooner", 'caption': '"My only regret is that I didn\'t do it sooner."\n\nIt\'s the most common thing patients say after hip or knee replacement. Not that it was hard. Not that it wasn\'t worth it.\n\nThat they wish they hadn\'t waited so long. 💙\n\nIf you\'ve been told you need a joint replacement — or you\'re wondering whether it\'s time — that conversation starts with your GP and a referral.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.', 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #PatientStories #PainFreeLife #DrChienWenLiew #NoRegrets #HipReplacementAdelaide', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-10-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "BACKGROUND: deep navy. Centred layout: thin light blue horizontal rule, then italic white quote 'My only regret is that I didn't do it sooner.' then attribution in small caps 'The most common thing patients say after joint replacement'. WORDMARK '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left. ORTHOPAEDICS 360 top centre in small tracking."},

{'id': 110, 'date': '2026-11-10', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'What Questions Should I Ask My GP About Joint Replacement?', 'caption': 'If your hip or knee pain has been affecting your daily life, your GP appointment is the best place to start the conversation about joint replacement.\n\nNot sure what to ask? Here are some questions that can help you get the most out of that appointment:\n\n❓ "Is my X-ray showing arthritis, and how severe is it?"\n❓ "Have I done enough conservative treatment, or is it time to consider surgery?"\n❓ "Can you refer me to an orthopaedic surgeon for an assessment?"\n❓ "What should I do to prepare myself before seeing the surgeon?"\n❓ "Are there any health issues (weight, blood pressure, diabetes) I should address first?"\n❓ "How long is the typical wait to see an orthopaedic surgeon in Adelaide?"\n\nYou don\'t need to be in crisis to ask for a referral. A consultation with an orthopaedic surgeon is simply an assessment — it doesn\'t commit you to anything.\n\nThe earlier you have the conversation, the more options you have.\n\n📞 Ask your GP to refer you to Dr Chien-Wen Liew at Orthopaedics 360, Eastwood Private Hospital.\n\n🌐 More information at drchienwenliew.com.au\n\nThis post contains general educational information only. Please consult your GP or specialist for advice tailored to your situation.', 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedics #GPReferral #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacementAdelaide #KneeReplacementAdelaide', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/questions-to-ask-your-surgeon/', 'image_file': '2026-11-10-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Modern GP consulting room, timber desk, computer, medical posters on wall, clean and professional, warm overhead lighting, no people, interior photography'},

{'id': 111, 'date': '2026-11-12', 'day': 'Thursday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Stat Card', 'topic': 'Stat Card — Joint Replacement in Under-65s Up 188%', 'caption': "Joint replacement isn't just for older Australians anymore. 📊\n\nThe data tells a clear story — more people in their 40s, 50s, and early 60s are choosing surgery to get their active lives back.\n\nYou don't have to wait until you can barely walk. You don't have to wait until you're retired. You don't have to keep managing pain that surgery could resolve.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\nSource: Australian Orthopaedic Association National Joint Replacement Registry (AOANJRR)\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AOANJRR #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #OsteoarthritisAwareness #YoungerPatients #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2026-11-12-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "BACKGROUND: deep navy with a soft light blue radial bloom centre. Large bold white stat text '188%' prominent centre, smaller text below 'increase in joint replacement in patients under 65 since 2010 in Australia' in light grey. Source line 'AOANJRR' small bottom right. WORDMARK '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left."},

{'id': 112, 'date': '2026-11-13', 'day': 'Friday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Haemostasis in TJR — TXA Protocols and Blood Conservation', 'caption': 'Tranexamic acid in total joint replacement: current protocols and the evidence behind them.\n\nBlood conservation in TJR has been one of the most impactful incremental improvements in arthroplasty over the past 15 years. The adoption of routine TXA has dramatically reduced allogenic transfusion rates — from historical rates of 20–30% in TKA and THA to well under 5% in most contemporary series.\n\nTXA mechanism\nTXA competitively inhibits the lysine binding sites on plasminogen, preventing fibrinolysis and stabilising formed clot. The dominant source of haemorrhage in TJR is surgical — not coagulation factor deficiency — making antifibrinolytic therapy highly effective.\n\nRoute of administration\nBoth intravenous (IV) and topical intra-articular (IA) TXA have Level 1 evidence supporting efficacy. Combined IV + IA protocols show additive benefit in some RCTs, particularly in TKA where tourniquet release and wound ooze are significant contributors. My current practice favours combined administration in primary TKA and IV administration in primary THA.\n\nDosing\nMost protocols use 1g IV pre-incision with a repeat dose at wound closure, or a single 2–3g dose. IA dosing typically uses 1–3g in 50–100mL saline injected prior to wound closure.\n\nSafety\nDespite early concerns, multiple large meta-analyses (including a Cochrane review of >100 RCTs) have not demonstrated elevated VTE risk with TXA in TJR patients receiving standard pharmacological thromboprophylaxis. It is safe to use in patients with a remote history of DVT/PE in most circumstances, though I discuss this individually.\n\nRelative contraindications\nActive thromboembolic event, acquired colour vision defect, or known TXA allergy. Renal impairment warrants dose adjustment.\n\nImpact on clinical practice\nEliminating routine pre-operative blood banking, reducing ICU admissions for post-operative anaemia, and enabling same-day discharge in appropriate patients are all downstream benefits of effective blood conservation.\n\n#TXA #BloodConservation #TotalHipReplacement #TotalKneeReplacement #Arthroplasty #PerioperativeMedicine #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-13-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Close-up of IV drip equipment and clear tubing on a clinical tray, soft diffuse lighting, white clinical surface, no people, clean medical still life photography'},

{'id': 113, 'date': '2026-11-15', 'day': 'Sunday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Infographic', 'topic': 'Hip Replacement Timeline — From First GP Appointment to Walking Without Pain', 'caption': "Wondering what the hip replacement journey actually looks like from start to finish? Here's the full timeline — step by step. 👇\n\nEveryone's journey is a little different, but this gives you a realistic picture of what to expect.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#HipReplacement #HipReplacementAdelaide #JointReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacementJourney #PatientEducation #DrChienWenLiew #HipHealth', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/anterior-approach-hip-replacement/', 'image_file': '2026-11-15-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "BACKGROUND: navy with subtle deep blue gradient. OVERLAY: dark navy panel left side. Vertical numbered timeline infographic: 1. GP appointment & referral | 2. Orthopaedic consultation (1–3 weeks) | 3. Decision to proceed & pre-op workup (2–4 weeks) | 4. Surgery day — Eastwood Private Hospital | 5. Day 1 — walking with support | 6. Week 2 — home, independent mobility | 7. Week 6 — driving, hydrotherapy cleared | 8. 3 months — most daily activities resumed | 9. 12 months — full recovery, enjoying life. WORDMARK '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left."},

{'id': 114, 'date': '2026-11-16', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'The Patient Who Delays — Clinical Consequences of Deferring Indicated Arthroplasty', 'caption': 'The clinical cost of deferring indicated arthroplasty: what the evidence tells us.\n\nIt is not uncommon for patients with clear radiographic and clinical indication for TJR to defer surgery — sometimes for years. While patient autonomy in surgical timing is paramount, there is a growing body of evidence that deferral carries its own risks that warrant frank discussion at the time of consultation.\n\nMusculoskeletal consequences\nOngoing pain leads to antalgic gait patterns, which impose abnormal loads on the contralateral hip, knee, and lumbar spine. Secondary musculoskeletal complaints — contralateral knee OA, lumbar degenerative disc disease, trochanteric bursitis — are over-represented in patients with prolonged arthroplasty deferral. Quadriceps and hip abductor atrophy accrues progressively and is not fully reversible at the time of eventual surgery.\n\nSurgical complexity\nBone stock loss, acetabular protrusio, and femoral deformity increase in severity over time in end-stage hip OA. While rarely prohibitive, more advanced disease is more technically demanding and associated with longer operative time and potentially increased component constraint requirements. The same applies in end-stage knee OA with significant varus or valgus deformity.\n\nPeri-operative risk\nDeconditioning, weight gain from reduced activity, and deterioration in metabolic control (diabetes, hypertension) all compound over time. Patients who defer and present for surgery several years later may be in significantly worse physiological condition than when first assessed.\n\nPost-operative outcomes\nA 2022 BMJ Open study found that patients with greater pre-operative functional limitation had lower absolute post-operative PROM scores despite similar relative improvement. The surgery works — but the starting point matters.\n\nThe takeaway for GP colleagues\nThe phrase "when you can\'t stand it anymore" is not evidence-based surgical timing. Functional decline, pain, and contralateral joint loading are legitimate clinical reasons to recommend timely referral and not indefinite deferral.\n\n#Arthroplasty #TJR #SurgicalTiming #PatientCounselling #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-16-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Empty modern hospital corridor with polished floors, receding perspective, warm overhead lighting, clean architecture, no people, professional healthcare interior photography'},

{'id': 115, 'date': '2026-11-17', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'How Long Does a Knee Replacement Operation Take? What the Patient Experiences', 'caption': "If you're preparing for a knee replacement, you might be wondering: what actually happens on the day? Here's a patient-centred view. 🏥\n\n⏰ The operation itself\nA primary total knee replacement typically takes 60–90 minutes of surgical time. The total time from entering the operating suite to being transferred to the recovery room is usually 2–3 hours, including anaesthetic preparation and immediate post-operative care.\n\n🌙 The night before\nYou'll fast from midnight (or as instructed by your anaesthetist). Some pre-op medications may be given the morning of surgery. Many patients find it helpful to pack a bag in advance and confirm their transport arrangements.\n\n🧘 Anaesthetic\nMost knee replacements are performed under spinal anaesthetic (you're awake but feel nothing from the waist down) with sedation if preferred, or under general anaesthetic — this is decided with your anaesthetist in advance. A regional nerve block is often added for post-operative pain relief.\n\n🛌 Recovery room\nYou'll spend 1–2 hours in the recovery room. The nursing staff monitor you closely and begin pain management. Most patients are surprised by how quickly they feel alert after a spinal anaesthetic.\n\n🚶 First steps\nA physiotherapist typically helps you stand and take a few steps on the same day as surgery, or the following morning. This early mobilisation is an important part of modern recovery protocols.\n\n🏠 Going home\nMost patients are discharged after 2–4 days. You'll leave with pain medications, wound care instructions, and a physiotherapy plan.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#KneeReplacement #KneeReplacementAdelaide #TotalKneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #KneeHealth #JointReplacement #WhatToExpect #PatientEducation #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/knee-replacement-recovery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-17-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Clean private hospital room with adjustable bed, warm lighting, bedside table with water glass, window with soft afternoon light, no people, calm and reassuring healthcare interior'},

{'id': 116, 'date': '2026-11-17', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Hip Arthritis Exercises — What Helps Before Surgery', 'caption': "If you've been diagnosed with hip arthritis and surgery is on the horizon, there's a lot you can do in the meantime to stay strong and make your recovery easier.\n\nHere are some exercises that are generally well-tolerated with hip OA — always check with your physiotherapist or GP first:\n\n🏊 Swimming and hydrotherapy\nThe most joint-friendly aerobic exercise available. Water supports your weight while allowing movement through a comfortable range.\n\n🚴 Stationary cycling\nLow impact, great for maintaining quad and hip flexor strength without loading the joint in a high-impact way.\n\n🧘 Seated hip strengthening\nExercises like seated knee raises, clam shells (lying down), and gentle bridges help maintain glute and abductor strength — the muscles most important for recovery.\n\n🚶 Walking\nEven short, regular walks help maintain cardiovascular fitness and muscle tone. Use a walking stick if it helps you move more comfortably and confidently.\n\n🔄 Gentle range-of-motion stretches\nMaintaining hip flexibility before surgery can make post-operative recovery smoother.\n\nThe goal isn't to push through pain — it's to stay as strong and mobile as possible going into surgery. This is called prehabilitation, and it genuinely improves outcomes.\n\nYour physiotherapist can create a specific program for your level of arthritis.\n\n🌐 Learn more at drchienwenliew.com.au\n\nThis post contains general educational information only. Please consult your GP or specialist for advice tailored to your situation.", 'hashtags': '#HipArthritis #HipReplacement #Prehabilitation #HipReplacementAdelaide #AdelaideOrthopaedics #Orthopaedics360 #JointHealth #HipHealth', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-17-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Bright home living room with exercise mat on timber floor, resistance bands neatly placed beside it, indoor plants, large window with garden view, no people, lifestyle wellness photography'},

{'id': 117, 'date': '2026-11-19', 'day': 'Thursday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Carousel', 'topic': "What to Tell Your Family When You're Having Joint Replacement Surgery", 'caption': "Your family and support people are a huge part of your recovery — but they often don't know what to expect either. Here's a practical guide to share with the people who'll be helping you. 👇\n\nSwipe through for what to tell them — and what to ask of them.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #RecoverySupport #PatientEducation #FamilySupport #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-19-instagram-slide1.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "SLIDE 1 — COVER: Deep navy background, bold white 'What to Tell Your Family Before Your Joint Replacement', light blue rule, ORTHOPAEDICS 360 top, wordmark '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left. |SLIDE| SLIDE 2 — 'The surgery itself' — navy panel: 'It's a 1–2 hour procedure. They won't need to wait at the hospital all day — your surgeon will call them when you're in recovery.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 3 — 'The first week home' — navy panel: 'This is when you'll need the most help. Meals, driving, getting in and out of bed, and having someone close by at night.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 4 — 'What NOT to do for me' — navy panel: 'Don't hover. Don't panic at every wince. Recovery involves some discomfort — that's normal. Encourage activity, not bed rest.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 5 — 'How to help with the home' — navy panel: 'Move items to bench height. Remove trip hazards (rugs, cords). Keep frequently used items accessible. Prepare easy meals in advance.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 6 — 'Week 2–6: the long middle' — navy panel: 'Recovery isn't linear. Some days are better than others. Patience and encouragement matter more than constant checking in.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 7 — 'When to call the surgeon' — navy panel: 'Fever above 38°C, wound redness or discharge, severe sudden pain, leg swelling — these need a call to the surgical team, not a wait-and-see.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 8 — CLOSING: navy, 'Your support makes recovery better. Thank you.' — italic, then 'drchienwenliew.com.au', wordmark '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left."},

{'id': 118, 'date': '2026-11-20', 'day': 'Friday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Enhanced Recovery — Sleep, Nutrition, and Hydration in the Perioperative Period', 'caption': 'Sleep, nutrition, and hydration in the peri-operative period: the overlooked pillars of enhanced recovery.\n\nThe ERAS (Enhanced Recovery After Surgery) paradigm has rightly focused on eliminating unnecessary fasting, optimising analgesia, and enabling early mobilisation. But three modifiable factors — sleep, nutritional status, and pre-operative hydration — remain under-discussed in arthroplasty pre-operative counselling.\n\nSleep\nPre-operative sleep disturbance is common in elective surgical patients and is an independent predictor of post-operative delirium, pain sensitivity, and extended length of stay. Patients with OSA should have their CPAP therapy optimised before surgery and bring their device for admission. For non-OSA patients, sleep hygiene counselling in the two weeks before surgery is low-cost and potentially high-impact.\n\nNutritional status\nMalnutrition — including occult malnutrition in obese patients with poor dietary quality — impairs wound healing, increases infection risk, and delays functional recovery. I now routinely use the MUST (Malnutrition Universal Screening Tool) or a simple albumin/pre-albumin check in patients over 70 or with BMI extremes. A course of oral nutritional supplementation in the 2–4 weeks before surgery is warranted in nutritionally at-risk patients.\n\nProtein intake specifically deserves attention. Post-operative muscle recovery depends on adequate protein substrate. Patients should be counselled to achieve 1.2–1.5g protein/kg/day pre-operatively, continued through the recovery period.\n\nHydration\nProlonged pre-operative fasting — often 10–12 hours in practice despite guidelines permitting clear fluids to 2 hours — is a source of unnecessary physiological stress. Modern anaesthetic guidelines (ANZCA) permit water and clear fluids to 2 hours before anaesthesia. I discuss this explicitly with patients and ask anaesthetic colleagues to reinforce it.\n\nThe aggregate effect of optimising all three domains is small per intervention — but meaningful in combination, particularly in the older, frailer patient cohort.\n\n#ERAS #PerioperativeMedicine #Nutrition #Arthroplasty #TJR #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #EnhancedRecovery', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-20-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Timber dining table with a balanced healthy meal — grilled protein, salad, whole grains — alongside a glass of water, natural window light, no people, clean food lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 119, 'date': '2026-11-22', 'day': 'Sunday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'The Christmas I Could Actually Enjoy — Being Present After Surgery', 'caption': "For some people, this Christmas will be completely different. Not because of decorations or food — but because they can actually be *there*. 🎄\n\nAfter years of sitting out. Arriving early to find a chair. Leaving events before everyone else because the pain got too much.\n\nHip and knee replacement surgery gives people back more than mobility. It gives them back their place in family life.\n\nThe patient who walked his daughter down the aisle without a stick.\nThe grandmother who got on the floor to play with her grandchildren at Christmas.\nThe retired teacher who did the full Boxing Day walk for the first time in four years.\n\nThese are real conversations from my clinic.\n\nIf surgery is something you've been considering — and Christmas is a reminder of what pain has taken from you — now is exactly the right time to start the conversation.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #ChristmasRecovery #PainFreeLife #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew #LifeAfterSurgery', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-22-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Warm Australian family Christmas table setting, timber table with festive decorations, fairy lights, green and gold centrepiece, plates and glasses, afternoon light, no people, festive lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 120, 'date': '2026-11-23', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Obesity and Surgical Timing in TJR — Updated BMI Thresholds and Shared Decision Making', 'caption': 'Obesity and surgical timing in TJR: revisiting the BMI threshold debate.\n\nThe relationship between obesity and arthroplasty outcomes is well-established. Elevated BMI is associated with increased peri-operative complication risk — specifically wound complications, periprosthetic joint infection (PJI), VTE, and revision surgery. These associations are dose-dependent and BMI >40 represents the highest-risk threshold in registry data.\n\nHowever, the historical practice of using BMI 40 as a hard surgical cutoff warrants more nuanced consideration.\n\nWhat the evidence now shows\n\n1. Weight loss before surgery is achievable in some patients, but difficult for most. Studies suggest that patients who are advised to lose weight before referral frequently do not — and instead experience continued functional decline and deconditioning. The average weight loss achieved in this group is under 5% of body weight.\n\n2. GLP-1 receptor agonists are changing this landscape. Semaglutide and tirzepatide are now achieving 15–22% body weight reduction in RCTs. This is genuinely new territory for surgical planning. I am increasingly seeing patients referred post-GLP-1 who have crossed below BMI thresholds that would previously have precluded surgery — and who are functionally and physiologically very different from non-medicated patients at the same BMI.\n\n3. Functional limitation and suffering matter. A patient with BMI 43 who cannot walk 200m, cannot sleep, and has exhausted all conservative options is not helped by indefinite deferral. Shared decision making requires an honest conversation about absolute risk, not a blanket threshold.\n\nMy current approach\nFor patients with BMI 35–40: surgery is appropriate with thorough pre-operative optimisation, enhanced peri-operative protocols, and clear counselling of elevated complication risk.\n\nFor patients with BMI >40: I discuss GLP-1 therapy (via endocrinology or GP) as a genuine pre-operative strategy if not already prescribed. Surgery is not categorically withheld, but a period of active weight optimisation is a reasonable expectation. I do not set an arbitrary cutoff — I set a risk conversation.\n\nFor GP colleagues: GLP-1 prescription for patients awaiting arthroplasty is a clinically legitimate and now evidence-informed use of these medications.\n\n#Obesity #TJR #Arthroplasty #GLP1 #SurgicalTiming #SharedDecisionMaking #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #BMI', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-23-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Bright modern clinic waiting room with comfortable seating, architectural lighting, artwork on walls, indoor plants, no people, premium private healthcare interior photography'},

{'id': 121, 'date': '2026-11-24', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Knee Replacement and Cycling — When and How to Get Back on the Bike', 'caption': "Good news for cyclists: knee replacement and cycling are a very compatible combination. 🚴\n\nHere's a realistic guide to getting back on the bike after a total knee replacement.\n\n\U0001f6de Stationary bike first (from ~6 weeks)\nMost patients start on a stationary bike at around 6 weeks, once the knee is bending to approximately 90–100°. The low-impact circular motion is actually great for the knee — it helps with range of motion, reduces stiffness, and builds quad strength. Start with low resistance and short sessions (10–15 min).\n\n🚴 Road or trail cycling (from ~3 months)\nOutdoor cycling can usually begin around 3 months, once you have good quad control, balance, and comfortable range of motion. Start on flat, smooth paths. Avoid rough terrain or prolonged climbs early on.\n\n🔧 Bike fit matters\nAfter knee replacement, a proper bike fit can make a significant difference to comfort. A slightly higher saddle height reduces knee flexion demands. Your physio can advise.\n\n⚠️ What to monitor\nSome swelling after the first few rides is normal — ice and elevation after activity helps. If you notice sharp or catching pain (rather than generalised muscle fatigue), let your surgical team know.\n\n💬 Most patients who were cyclists before surgery return to cycling — often with significantly less pain than before.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#KneeReplacement #KneeReplacementAdelaide #Cycling #ReturnToSport #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #KneeHealth #JointReplacement #ActiveRecovery #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/knee-replacement-recovery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-24-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "Cyclist's road bike leaning against a stone wall on a quiet Australian coastal path, morning light, green hills, no people, lifestyle cycling photography"},

{'id': 122, 'date': '2026-11-24', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'The Role of Your GP in the Joint Replacement Journey', 'caption': "Your GP is one of the most important people in your joint replacement journey — from that first conversation about pain all the way through to long-term recovery.\n\nHere's how your GP supports you at every stage:\n\n🩺 Early identification\nYour GP is often the first person to notice that hip or knee arthritis is significantly affecting your life. A weight-bearing X-ray and a conversation about conservative treatments is where the journey begins.\n\n📋 Referral\nWhen conservative management has been trialled and your quality of life is still significantly affected, your GP refers you to an orthopaedic surgeon. The referral letter matters — it helps the specialist understand your full picture.\n\n🏥 Pre-operative coordination\nBefore surgery, your GP may be asked to arrange blood tests, an ECG, or specialist clearance (e.g., cardiac). Managing your medications before admission — particularly blood thinners and diabetes medications — is a key GP role.\n\n💊 Post-operative care\nAfter you're discharged, your GP manages ongoing pain relief, wound checks, blood clot prevention medications, and any post-operative concerns that don't require a specialist visit.\n\n🔄 Long-term follow-up\nYour GP is part of your long-term joint health team — monitoring bone density, managing risk factors, and helping coordinate if any concerns arise with the joint replacement in the years ahead.\n\nJoint replacement is a team effort — and your GP is a central part of that team.\n\n🌐 More at drchienwenliew.com.au\n\nThis post contains general educational information only. Please consult your GP or specialist for advice tailored to your situation.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #GPCare #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedics #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacementAdelaide', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/questions-to-ask-your-surgeon/', 'image_file': '2026-11-24-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Modern GP practice consultation room with a desk, computer, patient chair, framed anatomy poster, indoor plant, warm lighting, no people, professional interior photography'},

{'id': 123, 'date': '2026-11-26', 'day': 'Thursday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Can I Have Both Hips Replaced at the Same Time? Bilateral vs Staged', 'caption': "Can both hips be replaced at the same time? It's a question I hear regularly — especially from patients who have arthritis in both hips. Here's the honest answer. 🦴\n\nThe two options:\n\n🔵 Staged bilateral hip replacement\nEach hip is replaced in a separate operation, typically 6–12 weeks apart. This is the most common approach. You recover from one hip, then proceed to the second. The advantage is lower peri-operative risk per procedure and a clearer recovery for each hip.\n\n🔵 Simultaneous bilateral hip replacement\nBoth hips replaced in a single anaesthetic. This can be appropriate for selected, fit, younger patients with bilateral severe OA who wish to minimise total time off work and recovery. It involves a longer operation and higher combined peri-operative risk — particularly blood loss and cardiac demand.\n\nWhat the evidence says:\nSimultaneous bilateral THA is performed safely in well-selected patients at high-volume centres. Peri-operative complication rates are higher than unilateral surgery but lower than two separate staged procedures combined. The AOANJRR reports that bilateral simultaneous THA represents a small but consistent proportion of primary hip procedures in Australia.\n\nPatient selection is critical:\nGood cardiac and respiratory reserve, younger age (typically under 70), no significant comorbidities, and strong support at home for the recovery period.\n\nMy practice:\nI offer staged bilateral as the default. I discuss simultaneous bilateral in appropriately selected patients where the clinical circumstances support it.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#HipReplacement #BilateralHipReplacement #HipReplacementAdelaide #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #TotalHipReplacement #JointReplacement #HipHealth #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/anterior-approach-hip-replacement/', 'image_file': '2026-11-26-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Two symmetrical X-ray light boxes mounted side by side on a white wall, glowing softly, no images on them, clean minimal medical interior, no people, architectural photography'},

{'id': 124, 'date': '2026-11-27', 'day': 'Friday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Long-Term Stewardship of the Joint Replacement Patient — GP Role and Red Flags', 'caption': "Long-term stewardship of the joint replacement patient: what GPs need to watch for.\n\nOnce a patient is 12 months post-TJR and discharged from orthopaedic follow-up, primary care becomes the front line for ongoing joint health. This is a topic I discuss at our shared care transitions — and one that I think deserves more attention in the GP literature.\n\nWhat normal late follow-up looks like\nMost patients with well-functioning TJR require no orthopaedic review beyond routine annual activity check-ins. There is no standard surveillance imaging schedule for asymptomatic implants in Australia — the AOANJRR data does not support routine annual radiographs in the absence of symptoms. I do recommend a baseline radiograph at 1 year, and then as clinically indicated.\n\nRed flags that warrant urgent orthopaedic review:\n1. Sudden onset pain in a previously pain-free joint — especially after a minor fall, stumble, or exertion. This can represent periprosthetic fracture.\n2. Increasing pain without injury — may indicate aseptic loosening, polyethylene wear, or early PJI (periprosthetic joint infection).\n3. Wound changes at any time — late wound breakdown, new sinus, or persistent drainage should raise PJI concern regardless of time from surgery.\n4. Systemic infection or bacteraemia — dental procedures, UTI, skin infections, and any source of bacteraemia in a patient with a joint replacement requires urgent discussion. Haematogenous seeding of implants remains a risk throughout the patient's life.\n5. Dislocation — acute THA dislocation is a surgical emergency. Patients typically present unable to weight bear, with shortening and rotation of the leg.\n\nAntibiotic prophylaxis\nI advise patients with TJR that dental procedures with gingival manipulation, urological procedures, and gastrointestinal procedures with mucosal breach warrant antibiotic prophylaxis for the first two years post-implant, and individually thereafter. Amoxicillin 2g orally 1 hour pre-procedure (or clindamycin 600mg if penicillin-allergic) is standard.\n\nI welcome direct contact from GP colleagues for any post-arthroplasty concerns — a quick call is always better than a delayed referral.\n\n#JointReplacement #PostOperativeCare #PJI #PeriprostheticJointInfection #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #GPEducation #TJR", 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/questions-to-ask-your-surgeon/', 'image_file': '2026-11-27-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Long hospital corridor with polished floors, symmetrical ceiling lights receding into distance, clean white walls, no people, professional healthcare architecture photography'},

{'id': 125, 'date': '2026-11-29', 'day': 'Sunday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Quote Card', 'topic': 'Quote Card — Every Step Forward Is Proof You Made the Right Decision', 'caption': '"Every step forward is proof you made the right decision."\n\nLate recovery can feel slow. Some days feel like you\'re going backwards. But if you were in pain before surgery and you\'re moving now — you are on the right path. 💙\n\nRecovery is not linear. Progress is not always visible day to day. But it is happening.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.', 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #RecoveryMotivation #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #LifeAfterSurgery #PainFreeLife #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/knee-replacement-recovery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-29-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "BACKGROUND: deep navy. Centred: thin light blue horizontal rule, italic white quote 'Every step forward is proof you made the right decision.' attribution below in small light grey caps 'Late recovery motivation — Orthopaedics 360'. WORDMARK '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left. ORTHOPAEDICS 360 top centre small tracking."},

{'id': 126, 'date': '2026-11-30', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Surgical Decision-Making in the Presence of Comorbidity — Cardiac, Renal, and Metabolic Risk', 'caption': 'Surgical decision-making in the presence of significant comorbidity: cardiac, renal, and metabolic risk in arthroplasty.\n\nElective TJR in patients with significant comorbidity requires integrated risk assessment that goes beyond ASA classification. Here is how I approach the most common comorbidity clusters in my practice.\n\nCardiac risk\nThe Revised Cardiac Risk Index (RCRI) remains the most widely validated pre-operative cardiac screening tool for non-cardiac surgery. For patients with an RCRI score of 2 or more, I request formal anaesthetic pre-assessment and often cardiology review. Specific concerns:\n\n- Recent ACS or CABG (within 60 days): elective surgery is deferred\n- Active heart failure: requires optimisation before proceeding; BNP and echo if not recent\n- Aortic stenosis: moderate-severe AS carries substantial peri-operative risk; cardiology valve review warranted\n- Anticoagulation for AF: bridging strategy and timing of cessation discussed with haematology or cardiology\n\nRenal impairment\nCKD stage 3b and above (eGFR <45) warrants nephrology review. Key concerns include:\n- Fluid management and avoiding hypovolaemia\n- NSAIDs contraindicated peri-operatively\n- Antibiotic prophylaxis dose adjustment (cefazolin is renally cleared)\n- Post-operative monitoring of creatinine, particularly with IV contrast if CT templating is used\n- Anaemia of chronic disease — often requires pre-operative iron therapy or ESA coordination with nephrology\n\nMetabolic risk\nPoorly controlled diabetes (HbA1c >69 mmol/mol / >8.5%) is associated with significantly elevated SSI and PJI risk. I ask GPs to assist in getting HbA1c below 64 mmol/mol (8%) before proceeding where possible. A 3–6 month window for glycaemic optimisation is clinically well-supported.\n\nLiver disease and coagulopathy\nSynthetic liver function should be checked (INR, albumin, platelets) in patients with known hepatic disease. Cirrhosis (particularly Child-Pugh B/C) carries very high peri-operative risk and is a near-contraindication to elective arthroplasty.\n\nThe clearer the risk profile at the time of referral, the more efficiently I can plan surgery and reduce last-minute deferrals.\n\n#Arthroplasty #ComorbidityManagement #PerioperativeRisk #CardiacRisk #RenalImpairment #Diabetes #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-11-30-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Neat medical case notes binder and stethoscope on a timber desk, warm overhead light, no people, professional clinical workspace photography'},

{'id': 127, 'date': '2026-12-01', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'What Is a Knee Osteotomy and Who Is It For?', 'caption': "Not everyone with knee pain needs a knee replacement. For some people, a knee osteotomy is a better option — especially if you're younger and active. Here's what it is and who it's for. 🦴\n\n🔵 What is a knee osteotomy?\nAn osteotomy is a procedure where bone is cut and realigned to redistribute load across the knee joint. In the most common type — a high tibial osteotomy (HTO) — the top of the shinbone is reshaped to shift weight away from the worn side of the joint.\n\n🔵 Who is it for?\nOsteotomy is typically considered in:\n- Patients under 55–60 who are active and physically demanding\n- Those with compartmental OA (wear on one side of the knee — usually medial)\n- Patients with a varus (bow-legged) alignment that concentrates load on the worn side\n- People who want to remain physically active in ways that would stress a knee replacement\n\n🔵 What does it involve?\nA small wedge of bone is removed or added to the tibia, then fixed with a plate. Recovery is longer than for partial or total knee replacement — full recovery is typically 6–12 months. A period of restricted weight-bearing is required.\n\n🔵 How long does it last?\nA well-performed HTO can delay or eliminate the need for joint replacement by 10–15 years in appropriate patients. It does not rule out future TKR if needed.\n\n🔵 Is it common?\nLess common than knee replacement — it requires careful patient selection. It's a procedure I discuss with patients when the clinical picture fits.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Knee Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#KneeOsteotomy #HighTibialOsteotomy #KneeHealth #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #KneeArthritis #JointHealth #DrChienWenLiew #KneeReplacementAdelaide', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/knee-replacement-recovery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-01-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': '3D render of a knee joint in cross-section showing bone alignment, clean anatomical illustration on dark navy background, medical education imagery, no people'},

{'id': 128, 'date': '2026-12-01', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Year in Review — What Orthopaedics 360 Is Grateful For in 2026', 'caption': "As December arrives, we find ourselves reflecting on what has been a remarkable year at Orthopaedics 360.\n\nIn 2026, Dr Chien-Wen Liew and the team have had the privilege of helping hundreds of patients in Adelaide and South Australia reclaim their mobility, their independence, and their quality of life through hip and knee replacement surgery.\n\nA few things we're especially grateful for this year:\n\n🙏 Every patient who trusted us with their care — and worked hard through their recovery\n\n🙏 The GPs and referring doctors who partner with us to give patients timely, well-coordinated access to surgery\n\n🙏 The team at Eastwood Private Hospital for their exceptional surgical and nursing support\n\n🙏 Everyone who followed our page, shared our posts, or asked a question that helped us create better educational content\n\nIf you or someone you love is considering hip or knee replacement — or just wants to understand what the journey looks like — we're here.\n\nThe best year to stop living in pain might just be 2027.\n\n🌐 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\nThis post contains general educational information only. Please consult your GP or specialist for advice tailored to your situation.", 'hashtags': '#Orthopaedics360 #YearInReview #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedics #DrChienWenLiew #HipReplacementAdelaide #Gratitude2026', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2026-12-01-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Warm sunset view over Adelaide city skyline from an elevated position, golden hour light, soft orange and blue sky, no people, aspirational cityscape photography'},

{'id': 129, 'date': '2026-12-03', 'day': 'Thursday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Carousel', 'topic': 'A Year of Questions Answered — Most-Asked Questions From Followers', 'caption': "You've been asking great questions all year. Here are the ones that came up again and again — and the answers that matter most. 👇\n\nSwipe through for our most-asked questions of 2026.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #PatientEducation #FAQs #DrChienWenLiew #HipHealth #KneeHealth', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/questions-to-ask-your-surgeon/', 'image_file': '2026-12-03-instagram-slide1.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "SLIDE 1 — COVER: Deep navy, bold white '2026: Your Questions, Answered', light blue rule, ORTHOPAEDICS 360 top, wordmark '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left. |SLIDE| SLIDE 2 — Q: 'How do I know if I need a hip or knee replacement?' — A: 'When arthritis significantly limits daily life and conservative treatments have been trialled, it's time to see an orthopaedic surgeon.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 3 — Q: 'How long is the recovery?' — A: 'Most patients are walking within 24 hours, driving at 6 weeks, and feeling substantially better by 3 months. Full recovery is 6–12 months.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 4 — Q: 'Will I need a walking frame or stick forever?' — A: 'Most patients are off walking aids by 6–8 weeks. The goal is full independence.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 5 — Q: 'Is it painful?' — A: 'Modern anaesthetic and pain protocols mean most patients are surprised by how manageable the pain is. You will have discomfort — not uncontrolled pain.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 6 — Q: 'How long does a joint replacement last?' — A: 'AOANJRR data shows 90%+ of hip replacements last 15–20 years. Implant technology continues to improve.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 7 — Q: 'Can I go back to sport?' — A: 'For most low-impact activity — walking, swimming, cycling, golf — yes. High-impact sport is discussed individually with your surgeon.' |SLIDE| SLIDE 8 — CLOSING: navy, 'More questions? Visit drchienwenliew.com.au', wordmark '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left."},

{'id': 130, 'date': '2026-12-04', 'day': 'Friday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Reflecting on a Year of Arthroplasty Practice — Evidence in 2026', 'caption': 'A clinical reflection on 2026: what the arthroplasty evidence showed us and what it means for practice.\n\nAs we approach the end of another year, it\'s worth pausing to consider the themes that shaped the literature and our conversations at orthopaedic meetings in 2026.\n\n1. Robotic-assisted surgery continues to mature — but outcome equivalence remains contested\nMultiple RCTs published in 2025–26 showed that robotic-assisted TKA produces more consistent component alignment and gap balancing than conventional instrumentation. However, functional outcome scores (Oxford, KOOS, FJS) at 1 and 2 years remain comparable. The debate has shifted from "does it work" to "which patients benefit most" — the answer likely lies in complex deformity, revision settings, and high-volume learning curve management.\n\n2. GLP-1 receptor agonists as peri-operative agents\nThis is the most significant emerging topic in elective arthroplasty planning. The 15–22% weight reduction achievable with semaglutide and tirzepatide is genuinely changing the risk profile of patients who were previously excluded from surgery. Questions remain about timing of cessation before anaesthesia (emerging guidance suggests ceasing 1 week pre-op for weekly dosing), but the clinical benefit is substantial.\n\n3. Periprosthetic joint infection — diagnosis is improving, treatment remains hard\nAlpha-defensin and leukocyte esterase lateral flow assays have simplified intra-operative PJI diagnosis. Two-stage revision remains the gold standard for chronic PJI, but DAIR (debridement, antibiotics, implant retention) is increasingly supported in acute haematogenous infection — particularly within 3 months of primary surgery or within 3 weeks of symptom onset.\n\n4. Patient-reported outcome measures are maturing\nThe shift to routine electronic PROM collection is accelerating. The challenge is not collection — it is integration into clinical workflow and using the data to identify outliers early rather than retrospectively.\n\n5. Same-day discharge after TJR — expanding but not universal\nThe evidence for same-day TKA and THA in appropriately selected patients is now strong. Length of stay of 1 night for most primary arthroplasty is achievable in the Australian private hospital setting.\n\nA year of incremental but meaningful progress.\n\n#Arthroplasty #TJR #Robotics #GLP1 #PJI #YearInReview #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2026-12-04-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Stack of open medical journals and a laptop on a timber desk, warm desk lamp light, no people, academic workspace photography'},

{'id': 131, 'date': '2026-12-06', 'day': 'Sunday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'This Year, I Got My Life Back — End-of-Year Reflection', 'caption': '"This year, I got my life back."\n\nIt\'s December. And for many patients who had hip or knee replacement surgery in 2026, the end of this year looks completely different to how it started.\n\nThe patient who couldn\'t get up from the couch at Christmas last year — and this year is planning to walk the Belair National Park with their family.\n\nThe retired nurse who had to stop working early because of knee pain — and this year returned to volunteer at her community garden.\n\nThe grandfather who sat on the sideline at every footy game for three years — and now stands for the whole last quarter.\n\nJoint replacement surgery is not a miracle. It\'s a procedure with a real recovery. But when the pain was the ceiling on everything — and now it isn\'t — the change is profound.\n\nIf 2026 was another year of waiting — 2027 can be the year you change things.\n\nConsultations are open. The conversation starts with your GP.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.', 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #LifeAfterSurgery #Orthopaedics360 #PainFreeLife #HipReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew #NewYear2027', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-06-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Two people walking through a sunlit Australian national park trail, gum trees, dappled light, green understorey, figures small and moving away into the distance, joyful lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 132, 'date': '2026-12-07', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Patient Journey Mapping in Arthroplasty — Decision Timelines', 'caption': 'Patient journey mapping in arthroplasty: what data tells us about how long patients wait — and why.\n\nThe concept of patient journey mapping has moved from the health administration literature into clinical practice improvement in recent years. In arthroplasty, the data reveals a consistently long and often unnecessary gap between symptom onset and surgical intervention.\n\nKey data points from the Australian context\n\nThe AOANJRR and broader Australian health data suggest that the mean time from first GP presentation with hip or knee OA symptoms to orthopaedic surgery is approximately 5–7 years. This is not primarily a waiting list problem — it reflects patient and clinician decision-making behaviour throughout the journey.\n\nWhere the delays occur\n\nStage 1 — GP to referral: Average 18–24 months. Patients often cycle through multiple GP visits before a referral is made. Contributing factors include patient reluctance, GP uncertainty about threshold, and under-documentation of functional limitation.\n\nStage 2 — Referral to consultation: Variable. Private patients in Adelaide typically wait 1–3 weeks. Public patients face significantly longer waits (months to over a year in some cases).\n\nStage 3 — Consultation to surgery: Average 2–4 months in private practice. This is often extended by patient deferral post-consultation — the "I\'m not ready yet" phenomenon — which accounts for a significant proportion of overall delay.\n\nStage 4 — Surgery to meaningful recovery: 3–6 months for most patients with primary TJR.\n\nWhat this means for GP colleagues\nThe most impactful intervention is earlier, lower-threshold referral. A patient does not need to be in crisis to be referred. An orthopaedic assessment at BMI 35, WOMAC score in the moderate range, and 12 months of conservative management is clinically appropriate — and earlier referral preserves more options (including non-surgical ones).\n\n#PatientJourney #Arthroplasty #TJR #GPReferral #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #AOANJRR #KneeReplacement #HipReplacement', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2026-12-07-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Minimalist whiteboard with a simple horizontal timeline drawn in marker, blurred background of a modern meeting room, no people, clean business process photography'},

{'id': 133, 'date': '2026-12-08', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Can I Drink Alcohol After Joint Replacement Surgery?', 'caption': "One of the questions patients sometimes feel a little awkward asking — so let's just answer it. 🍷\n\nCan you drink alcohol after hip or knee replacement?\n\nHere's the practical breakdown:\n\n🚫 First 2 weeks: avoid alcohol entirely\nIn the immediate post-operative period, alcohol interacts with pain medications — particularly opioids and certain anti-inflammatories — and can increase the risk of bleeding, nausea, and dizziness. Most post-op medications carry explicit alcohol warnings. This is a firm no during the early phase.\n\n⚠️ Weeks 2–6: caution and moderation\nOnce you're off stronger pain medications and your wound is healing, small amounts of alcohol are generally not prohibited — but there are still reasons for care:\n- Alcohol thins the blood (mild anticoagulant effect) — not ideal while on post-op thromboprophylaxis\n- It can interfere with sleep quality, which is critical to recovery\n- Dehydration from alcohol can worsen joint swelling\n\n✅ After 6 weeks and off medications: social drinking in moderation is generally fine\nMost patients are off thromboprophylaxis by 5–6 weeks post-op. After this point and once medications are ceased, moderate alcohol intake is not contraindicated. Standard guidelines (no more than 2 standard drinks per day, alcohol-free days each week) apply.\n\n💊 Always check with your surgeon or pharmacist about your specific medications before having a drink. Every patient's medication plan is different.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #RecoveryTips #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #PatientEducation #HipReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/knee-replacement-recovery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-08-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Two glasses of wine on a timber table at a social gathering, warm background light, soft bokeh, no people in focus, lifestyle entertaining photography'},

{'id': 134, 'date': '2026-12-08', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Planning Your Joint Replacement in 2027 — How to Get Started', 'caption': "If you've been thinking about hip or knee replacement in 2027, December is actually the perfect time to start planning.\n\nHere's why — and what to do first.\n\n📅 Why start now?\n\nThe most common mistake is waiting until the pain is unbearable. By that point, you've often lost muscle, missed months of activity, and pushed your surgery further into the year than necessary.\n\nStarting the conversation now means:\n- A consultation in January or February 2027\n- Surgery potentially by March or April\n- A full recovery well before the following summer\n\n🗺️ Step 1: Talk to your GP\nAsk for a referral to an orthopaedic surgeon. If you have recent X-rays, bring them. If not, your GP can organise weight-bearing views.\n\n🗺️ Step 2: Book a consultation\nOnce referred, Dr Liew's team will contact you within 2 business days to arrange an appointment.\n\n🗺️ Step 3: Get assessed\nAt the consultation, you'll discuss your symptoms, your goals, your X-rays, and whether surgery is the right option for you — and when.\n\n🗺️ Step 4: Start preparing\nIf surgery is recommended, there is plenty you can do to improve your outcome: staying active, managing weight, optimising health conditions.\n\n2027 can be the year you stop managing pain and start living without it.\n\n📞 Ask your GP to refer you to Dr Chien-Wen Liew, Orthopaedics 360, Eastwood Private Hospital, Adelaide.\n\n🌐 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\nThis post contains general educational information only. Please consult your GP or specialist for advice tailored to your situation.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #HipReplacementAdelaide #KneeReplacementAdelaide #AdelaideOrthopaedics #Orthopaedics360 #Plan2027', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-08-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Open weekly diary planner for January 2027, pen resting on page, clean timber desk, morning light, no people, organised planning lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 135, 'date': '2026-12-10', 'day': 'Thursday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Stat Card', 'topic': 'Stat Card — Average Wait 2.5 Years From Symptoms to Surgeon', 'caption': "2.5 years. That's the average time Australians wait from first experiencing joint pain to finally seeing an orthopaedic surgeon. 📊\n\nThat's 2.5 years of:\n- Pain limiting daily activities\n- Missing out on things that matter\n- Muscle and function declining\n- Managing instead of fixing\n\nYou don't have to wait that long.\n\nA referral from your GP is all it takes to start. Consultations with Dr Liew are typically available within 1–3 weeks of referral.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #OsteoarthritisTreatment #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacementAdelaide #ActNow #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2026-12-10-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "BACKGROUND: deep navy with soft light blue radial bloom. Large bold white '2.5 years' prominent centre. Smaller grey text below 'The average wait from first joint pain to seeing an orthopaedic surgeon in Australia'. Then bold white 'You don't have to.' WORDMARK '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left."},

{'id': 136, 'date': '2026-12-11', 'day': 'Friday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Arthroplasty in 2026 — Year-End Evidence Review', 'caption': 'Arthroplasty in 2026: a year-end evidence review for orthopaedic and GP colleagues.\n\nA selection of the themes and publications that shaped my thinking this year.\n\nHip arthroplasty\n\nAnterior approach vs posterior — the debate continues, but the data increasingly supports equivalence in 5-year outcomes between experienced surgeons using either approach. The anterior approach remains preferred in my practice for primary uncomplicated THA due to early functional advantages in the first 6 weeks, but patient selection and surgeon experience remain more important than approach choice.\n\nThe CORAIL stem 20-year data (published in JBJS 2025) confirmed excellent survivorship exceeding 95% at 20 years in primary THA. This is important for counselling younger patients about implant longevity.\n\nKnee arthroplasty\n\nPatient-specific instrumentation (PSI) — a second large RCT failed to demonstrate functional superiority over conventional instrumentation at 2 years. The cost-benefit case for PSI in standard primary TKA is increasingly difficult to defend outside robotics platforms.\n\nKinematic alignment in TKA: a multicentre RCT published in The Lancet this year showed no significant difference in Oxford Knee Score between kinematic and mechanical alignment at 2 years. Longer-term data is awaited.\n\nRehabilitation\n\nTelerehabilitation vs in-person physio: a well-designed Australian RCT showed non-inferiority for telerehab in primary TKA recovery up to 6 months. This has significant implications for patients in regional SA and for healthcare system efficiency.\n\nMy key takeaway from 2026\nThe quality of the peri-operative journey — pain management, sleep, nutrition, early mobilisation, clear patient education — is now as important to outcomes as the choice of implant or approach. The literature is catching up with what clinicians who do high-volume arthroplasty have known for years.\n\n#Arthroplasty #YearInReview #THA #TKA #EvidenceBasedMedicine #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2026-12-11-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Stack of medical journals and printed research papers on a desk with a warm desk lamp, close crop, dark background, academic study atmosphere, no people'},

{'id': 137, 'date': '2026-12-13', 'day': 'Sunday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': "Don't Let Another Year Go By in Pain — New Year Motivation", 'caption': 'Every January, people make promises to themselves.\n\nGet fitter. Eat better. Do the thing they\'ve been putting off.\n\nAnd then — for many people living with hip or knee pain — another year passes. And nothing changes. Because making the call felt too big, or the timing wasn\'t right, or they told themselves they\'d manage a bit longer.\n\nWe hear this story in clinic constantly. And we also hear what comes after surgery:\n\n"Why did I wait so long?"\n"I had no idea how much pain I\'d been normalising."\n"I feel like I have my life back."\n\nYou don\'t need to hit rock bottom before you seek help. You don\'t need to be unable to walk before the conversation is worth having.\n\nIf hip or knee pain has been a constant presence in your life — and 2026 didn\'t change that — 2027 can.\n\nThe first step is asking your GP for a referral.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.', 'hashtags': '#NewYear2027 #JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #PainFreeLife #HipReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew #NewYearNewStart', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-13-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Person walking alone along an empty beach at sunrise, figure small and distant, warm orange horizon light reflecting on wet sand, no faces visible, hopeful and peaceful lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 138, 'date': '2026-12-14', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Social Prescribing and Community Support in Arthroplasty Recovery', 'caption': "Social prescribing and community support in arthroplasty recovery: an underutilised dimension of care.\n\nThe biomedical model of arthroplasty recovery — exercise, analgesia, wound care, physiotherapy — is well-established. Less formalised is the evidence around social factors and community engagement in recovery outcomes.\n\nWhat the evidence shows\nA 2024 Cochrane review of social interventions in elective surgery recovery found that patients with strong social support networks had:\n- Lower rates of post-operative depression and anxiety\n- Shorter length of stay and reduced readmission\n- Higher reported satisfaction with surgical outcome\n- Better adherence to physiotherapy programmes\n\nIn arthroplasty specifically, social isolation is a risk factor for post-operative delirium in older patients, reduced functional recovery, and lower PROM scores at 6 and 12 months.\n\nSocial prescribing in practice\nSocial prescribing — the formal connection of patients to non-clinical community resources — is gaining traction in Australian primary care. In the arthroplasty context, this might include:\n- Referral to a local walking group or community gym programme post-operatively\n- Peer support from patients who have undergone similar procedures (some hospitals now facilitate this)\n- Community occupational therapy home assessment rather than a purely clinical pre-op checklist\n- Volunteer driver programmes for patients without transport for post-op physiotherapy\n\nThe role of GP and allied health\nGPs and care coordinators are better placed than surgeons to implement social prescribing — they know the patient's context, family, and community. I increasingly encourage my referring GPs to consider the social picture when planning and supporting recovery.\n\nFor isolated patients — those without family nearby, recent migrants, patients with limited language proficiency, or those in remote areas — this dimension of care is not optional. It is clinical.\n\n#SocialPrescribing #Arthroplasty #TJR #RecoverySupport #PatientCentredCare #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #GPEducation", 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-14-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Community garden with raised beds and a gathering area, green plants, warm afternoon light filtering through pergola, no people, peaceful outdoor community space photography'},

{'id': 139, 'date': '2026-12-15', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Hip Replacement and Gardening in Summer — Back to the Veggie Patch', 'caption': "The veggie patch is calling. Can you get back to gardening after a hip replacement? 🌱 Yes — with a few adjustments. Here's what to know for summer.\n\n🌿 When can I start gardening again?\nMost patients can return to light gardening from around 6–8 weeks post-op. Heavy digging, deep bending, or prolonged kneeling takes longer — typically 3–4 months, depending on how your recovery is tracking.\n\n🪑 Raised garden beds are your best friend\nAt ground level, hip precautions (avoiding deep hip flexion and certain rotation movements in the first 3 months) make traditional gardening challenging. Raised beds at bench height eliminate this problem entirely. Many patients find hip replacement motivates a garden redesign — and it genuinely makes gardening safer and more enjoyable long-term.\n\n🧰 Adaptive tools\nLong-handled tools — hoes, rakes, grabbers — allow you to tend low beds without bending from the hip. Garden kneelers with handles can help if kneeling is required.\n\n🌞 Summer gardening tips\n- Garden in the morning or evening to avoid midday heat\n- Keep water nearby — staying hydrated matters even more during recovery\n- Short sessions with rests beat marathon gardening at this stage\n\n🪴 The goal\nMost hip replacement patients are back to full gardening by 3–4 months — and many report that being able to tend the garden again is one of the most meaningful milestones of recovery.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#HipReplacement #HipReplacementAdelaide #GardeningAfterSurgery #JointReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #LifeAfterHipReplacement #ReturnToActivity #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/anterior-approach-hip-replacement/', 'image_file': '2026-12-15-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Lush raised vegetable garden beds in an Australian backyard, summer sunshine, green tomato plants and herbs, timber raised beds at waist height, no people, lifestyle gardening photography'},

{'id': 140, 'date': '2026-12-15', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': "Summer and Joint Pain — Why Hot Weather Sometimes Helps and Sometimes Doesn't", 'caption': "Summer is here — and for people with hip or knee arthritis, the season brings a mixed bag.\n\nSome people feel much better in the heat. Others find the humidity and temperature changes trigger more pain. Here's why both things are true.\n\n☀️ Why summer can help:\n- Warmth relaxes muscles and surrounding soft tissue, reducing tension around an arthritic joint\n- More activity (walking, swimming) improves circulation and reduces stiffness\n- Better sleep (for those who sleep better in warmer weather) reduces pain sensitivity\n- Improved mood from longer days and sunlight can raise pain threshold\n\n🌧️ Why summer can be harder:\n- Heat causes vasodilation — increased blood flow to the joint can increase inflammatory swelling\n- Humidity in some climates worsens inflammatory arthritis (though Adelaide summers are typically dry)\n- Dehydration from heat reduces cartilage hydration and can worsen joint stiffness\n- Increased activity can accelerate wear symptoms in advanced OA\n\nWhat to do:\nStay well hydrated. Keep up gentle movement. Use ice for swelling, heat for stiffness. Listen to your body.\n\nAnd if summer is highlighting how much pain is affecting your life — that's useful information. It's a signal that a conversation with your GP about a referral might be timely.\n\n🌐 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\nThis post contains general educational information only. Please consult your GP or specialist for advice tailored to your situation.", 'hashtags': '#JointPain #Osteoarthritis #HipArthritis #KneeArthritis #AdelaideOrthopaedics #Orthopaedics360 #SummerHealth #HipReplacementAdelaide', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2026-12-15-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Australian outdoor patio in summer, timber table with condensation on glasses, garden in soft focus background, warm light, no people, relaxed summer lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 141, 'date': '2026-12-17', 'day': 'Thursday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Quote Card', 'topic': 'Quote Card — 2027 Is the Year I Stop Saying Eventually', 'caption': '"2027 is the year I stop saying \'eventually.\'"\n\nEventually I\'ll book the appointment.\nEventually it\'ll get better on its own.\nEventually I\'ll be ready.\n\nPain doesn\'t respond to "eventually." But you do.\n\nThis December, make the decision. Ask your GP for a referral. Start the year with something real.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.', 'hashtags': '#NewYear2027 #JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #NewYearMotivation #HipReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew #StopWaiting', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-17-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'BACKGROUND: deep navy. Centred: thin light blue rule, large italic white quote \'2027 is the year I stop saying "eventually."\' attribution below in small light grey caps \'New Year intention — Orthopaedics 360\'. WORDMARK \'(DR) LIEW\' bottom-left.'},

{'id': 142, 'date': '2026-12-18', 'day': 'Friday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Planning Elective Arthroplasty in 2027 — What GPs Can Do Now', 'caption': 'Planning elective arthroplasty in 2027: practical steps GPs can take now to help patients prepare.\n\nJanuary consistently brings an increase in arthroplasty referrals — patients energised by a new year, resolved to address pain they\'ve been managing for too long. Here\'s how GP colleagues can make the most of this window.\n\n1. Identify patients who are overdue for referral\nPatients who have had hip or knee OA documented in the notes, have been prescribed long-term NSAIDs or opioids for joint pain, or who have attended multiple appointments for pain management over the past 12 months are candidates for a direct conversation about referral. You don\'t need to wait for them to raise it.\n\n2. Order weight-bearing X-rays before the referral\nA plain weight-bearing AP pelvis (hip) or standing AP, lateral and skyline views (knee) makes the consultation far more efficient. Radiology reports framed in clinical context — not just "moderate OA changes" — are helpful. If you note significant joint space narrowing, valgus/varus deformity, or subchondral changes, document this explicitly.\n\n3. Initiate pre-operative optimisation early\nIf there are modifiable risk factors — suboptimal HbA1c, BMI >35, active smoking, anaemia, uncontrolled hypertension — addressing these before the orthopaedic appointment saves time later. Patients referred with well-controlled comorbidities have shorter time-to-surgery once seen.\n\n4. Counsel patients that a consultation is not a commitment\nA significant proportion of patients who would benefit from orthopaedic assessment resist referral because they fear being "pressured into surgery." Reassuring them that a consultation is simply an assessment — and that they remain in full control of any decision — reduces this barrier.\n\n5. Ask about goals and activity expectations\nUnderstanding what the patient wants to get back to is as important as their pain score. A 58-year-old who wants to return to regular golf has different expectations — and different urgency — than a 74-year-old whose primary goal is pain-free walking. Capturing this in the referral letter helps me tailor the consultation.\n\nThank you to all the GP colleagues who referred patients in 2026 — I look forward to working with you in 2027.\n\n#GPReferral #Arthroplasty #ElectiveSurgery #TJR #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #Planning2027', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-18-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'GP practice consultation room with a computer screen showing a referral letter draft, tidy desk, warm indoor light, no people, professional healthcare workspace photography'},

{'id': 143, 'date': '2026-12-20', 'day': 'Sunday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Infographic', 'topic': 'Your 2027 Joint Health Action Plan', 'caption': "If 2027 is going to be different — this is the plan. Simple steps to go from joint pain to a consultation, and from a consultation to a decision. 👇\n\nShare this with someone who's been putting it off.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#JointHealth #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #HipReplacementAdelaide #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #NewYear2027 #ActionPlan #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-20-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': "BACKGROUND: navy blue with subtle light blue gradient. OVERLAY: semi-transparent dark panel. Numbered vertical action plan infographic: 1. Talk honestly with your GP about how pain is affecting your life | 2. Ask for weight-bearing X-rays | 3. Request a referral to an orthopaedic surgeon | 4. Attend a consultation — ask your questions | 5. Make an informed decision, in your own time | 6. Start prehabilitation — stay strong before surgery | 7. Surgery, recovery, and the life you've been waiting for. WORDMARK '(DR) LIEW' bottom-left."},

{'id': 144, 'date': '2026-12-21', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Prediction Models for Arthroplasty Outcome — What Patient Factors Matter Most', 'caption': 'Prediction models for arthroplasty outcome: what patient factors most reliably predict result.\n\nThe development of pre-operative prediction models for TJR outcome has accelerated significantly with the availability of large PROM datasets from national registries. Here is a synthesis of where the evidence currently stands.\n\nFactors with robust evidence for outcome prediction\n\n1. Pre-operative pain and function severity (WOMAC, OKS, HOOS)\nParadoxically, patients with the worst pre-operative scores show the greatest absolute improvement but achieve the lowest absolute post-operative scores. Patients with moderate pre-operative function tend to achieve the best absolute post-operative function. This has implications for surgical timing — the "wait until it\'s bone on bone" philosophy may delay surgery to the point where recovery potential is diminished.\n\n2. Age\nAdvanced age is associated with lower absolute post-operative function but not with reduced relative improvement. Age alone is not a contraindication, but it contextualises expectations.\n\n3. Psychological factors — depression, catastrophising, and pain anxiety\nThese are among the strongest independent predictors of poor patient-reported outcome in TJR, with effect sizes comparable to implant type. The Pain Catastrophising Scale (PCS) and the Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale (HADS) are validated screening tools. Patients scoring high on catastrophising benefit from pre-operative pain psychology referral.\n\n4. Obesity\nBMI >40 is independently associated with lower WOMAC and OKS at 1 and 2 years, even after successful implantation. The effect is mediated partly by ongoing systemic inflammation and partly by biomechanical load on the implant and surrounding soft tissue.\n\n5. Contralateral joint status\nPatients with bilateral hip or knee OA may have limited post-operative function due to the contralateral joint limiting gait rehabilitation. This is a counselling point, not a contraindication.\n\n6. Social support\nAs noted in the social prescribing literature, patients with strong support show better adherence and recovery. This is now incorporated into several pre-operative risk stratification tools.\n\n7. Surgeon and institution volume\nHigh-volume surgeons and centres consistently outperform low-volume on major complication rates, revision rates, and functional outcomes in registry data.\n\nThe clinical implication is that arthroplasty outcomes are substantially pre-determined before the patient enters the operating room. The surgeon\'s role extends well beyond technique — it includes identifying and modifying risk factors, setting appropriate expectations, and addressing psychological barriers.\n\n#Arthroplasty #Outcomes #TJR #PROM #PredictionModel #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #PainCatastrophising', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-21-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Abstract data visualisation — a soft glowing graph or scatter plot on a dark navy background, data science aesthetic, no people, digital analytics concept photography'},

{'id': 145, 'date': '2026-12-22', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Christmas Seasonal Post — Wishing You a Pain-Free Festive Season', 'caption': "🎄 From all of us at Orthopaedics 360 — wishing you and your family a warm, joyful, and pain-free festive season.\n\nTo every patient who took the brave step of choosing surgery this year: we are so proud of your recovery.\n\nTo everyone who followed along, asked questions, shared our posts, or encouraged someone they love to seek help — thank you.\n\nAnd to those still weighing up the decision: we'll be here in the new year, ready to help when you're ready.\n\nMerry Christmas from Dr Chien-Wen Liew and the Orthopaedics 360 team. 💙\n\n📍 Eastwood Private Hospital, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au", 'hashtags': '#MerryChristmas #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #DrChienWenLiew #HappyHolidays #ChristmasAdelaide #PainFreeLife', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au', 'image_file': '2026-12-22-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Elegant Christmas table setting with candles, red and green centrepiece, champagne flutes and white plates on a white linen tablecloth, warm golden light, no people, festive lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 146, 'date': '2026-12-22', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Merry Christmas From Dr Chien-Wen Liew and Orthopaedics 360', 'caption': 'Merry Christmas from Dr Chien-Wen Liew and the team at Orthopaedics 360. 🎄\n\nThis time of year is a reminder of what matters most — family, friends, and being present for the moments that count.\n\nFor many of our patients, this Christmas looks different from last year. More movement, less pain, and the ability to be fully there.\n\nTo every patient, GP, and supporter who has been part of our community in 2026 — thank you. It has been a privilege to be part of your journeys.\n\nWishing you a restful, joyful, and healthy festive season.\n\nWe will be back in the new year, ready to help make 2027 the year you make the change.\n\n🌐 drchienwenliew.com.au', 'hashtags': '#MerryChristmas #Orthopaedics360 #DrChienWenLiew #HipReplacementAdelaide #AdelaideOrthopaedics #Christmas2026', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au', 'image_file': '2026-12-22-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Australian garden Christmas party scene with festive lights strung in a tree, outdoor table with food and drinks, late evening warm light, no people, relaxed summer festive photography'},

{'id': 147, 'date': '2026-12-24', 'day': 'Thursday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'The Christmas Present No One Expected — Moving Without Pain', 'caption': "No one puts it on their Christmas list.\n\nNo one wraps it up or puts it under a tree.\n\nBut for some families this Christmas, the best present is simply watching someone they love move freely. Without wincing. Without the careful lowering into a chair. Without the slow walk to the car. Without the excuse to leave early because the pain is too much. 🎄\n\nJoint replacement gives this back.\n\nNot just to the patient — but to everyone who loves them.\n\nThe partner who has been watching them struggle for years.\nThe adult children who have been managing the worry quietly.\nThe grandchildren who just want to sit on Grandma's lap on the floor.\n\nIf this resonates — that's worth paying attention to.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #ChristmasGift #PainFreeLife #HipReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew #FamilyChristmas', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-24-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Multi-generational family Christmas dinner setting viewed from above, timber table with food and festive decorations, hands and plates visible but faces cropped or soft, warm light, joyful gathering photography'},

{'id': 148, 'date': '2026-12-27', 'day': 'Sunday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': "New Year's Resolution — Stop Putting Off Joint Replacement", 'caption': 'It\'s that week between Christmas and New Year — and maybe you\'re doing what a lot of people do: quietly thinking about what you want to change.\n\nIf hip or knee pain has been on your list for a while now — this year, let it be more than a thought.\n\nHere\'s what "making the decision" actually looks like in practice:\n\n1️⃣ Have an honest conversation with yourself about how much pain is affecting your daily life.\n\n2️⃣ Book a GP appointment. Ask for a referral to an orthopaedic surgeon. That\'s it — one phone call.\n\n3️⃣ Come to a consultation. Ask every question you have. Make an informed decision — no pressure, in your own time.\n\n4️⃣ If surgery is right for you, get started on prehabilitation — physio, strength, sleep, nutrition — while you wait.\n\n5️⃣ Have the surgery. Do the recovery. Get your life back.\n\nMost people who delay say they were waiting until the time was "right." The time doesn\'t announce itself. It just passes.\n\nThis year, you make it the right time.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.', 'hashtags': '#NewYearsResolution #JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #NewYear2027 #HipReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew #StopWaiting', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-27-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Clean open notebook with a pen and a simple handwritten list on a timber table, morning coffee, warm natural light, no people, fresh start lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 149, 'date': '2026-12-28', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'The New Year Arthroplasty Surge — Managing Increased Referrals Efficiently', 'caption': 'The January arthroplasty referral surge: practical strategies for managing increased demand.\n\nJanuary consistently produces a significant increase in orthopaedic referrals. This is driven by patient resolution behaviour — the new year framing motivates action on health decisions that have been deferred — and by the natural inflection point at the end of the holiday period.\n\nFor GP practices, this creates a concentrated period of referral generation. Here is what helps.\n\nFrom the GP practice side:\n\n1. Batch referral review sessions\nRather than generating arthroplasty referrals one at a time as patients present, some practices find a weekly "joint referral review" session useful — catching patients who have been repeatedly presenting with joint pain and haven\'t yet been referred.\n\n2. Standardise what the referral includes\nReferrals that include weight-bearing X-ray, duration of symptoms, conservative treatments trialled, relevant comorbidities, and patient goals reach the right priority queue immediately. Incomplete referrals create back-and-forth delay.\n\n3. Initiate pre-operative optimisation immediately\nRather than waiting for the orthopaedic appointment to trigger workup, GPs can initiate HbA1c optimisation, iron supplementation for anaemia, and smoking cessation at the time of referral generation. This shortens the time-to-surgery once the patient is seen.\n\nFrom our practice:\nWe triage incoming referrals by urgency and complexity. Patients with significant functional limitation, rapid progression, or complex comorbidities are prioritised. We contact referred patients within 2 business days and aim for first appointment within 2–3 weeks.\n\nI appreciate GP colleagues who note urgency or specific concerns in the referral body — it helps us triage appropriately.\n\nFor any GP who has a patient ready to be referred but is uncertain about the letter content or urgency, I am available for a brief phone discussion.\n\nHappy new year to all my GP colleagues — I look forward to working with you in 2027.\n\n#GPReferral #Arthroplasty #TJR #ReferralManagement #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2026-12-28-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'GP practice front reception desk with an organised calendar planner, referral pads, computer screen, indoor plant, bright clinical lighting, no people, professional medical administration photography'},

{'id': 150, 'date': '2026-12-29', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'What Changes in January for Joint Replacement Bookings?', 'caption': "Thinking about booking a hip or knee replacement consultation in January? Here's what to know about how timing works in the new year. 📅\n\n📋 Consultations: available from early January\nDr Liew's practice is open and accepting new referrals from the start of the year. January is actually a great time to be seen — there's often a window of availability before the full post-holiday rush.\n\n🏥 Surgery scheduling: typically 4–8 weeks from consultation\nIf you decide to proceed after your consultation, surgery can often be scheduled 4–8 weeks out depending on Eastwood Private Hospital availability. January consultations often translate to February or March surgeries — a timeline that sets patients up for recovery through autumn.\n\n⏳ Wait times can increase in Q1\nDemand for orthopaedic consultations spikes in January and February as people act on new year decisions. If you're hoping to be seen quickly, requesting a referral now — rather than in February — gives you the best position.\n\n🗓️ Private health insurance considerations\nIf your private health insurance has a waiting period for hospital benefits, January is also a good time to check your cover and confirm any waiting periods have been served. Your insurer can advise.\n\nThe bottom line: if 2027 is the year, January is the month to start.\n\nAsk your GP for a referral this week.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.", 'hashtags': '#JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #BookNow #HipReplacementAdelaide #KneeReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew #NewYear2027', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-29-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Wall calendar showing January 2027 with several dates circled in pen, warm desk light, timber background, no people, planning and organisation lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 151, 'date': '2026-12-29', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'New Year, New Start — Book Your Consultation in 2027', 'caption': 'New year, new start. If you\'ve been living with hip or knee pain — 2027 is the year to do something about it.\n\nHere\'s the honest truth about joint replacement surgery:\n\n✅ It works. AOANJRR data shows 90%+ of hip and knee replacements are still functioning well at 15–20 years.\n\n✅ Recovery is manageable. Most patients are walking the same day or the next morning. Most are home within 2–4 days.\n\n✅ The results are life-changing. The most common thing patients say is: "I wish I\'d done it sooner."\n\n✅ You don\'t have to wait until you can barely walk. The best results come from planned, well-prepared surgery — not crisis intervention.\n\nStarting the process is simpler than most people think:\n\n1. Book an appointment with your GP\n2. Ask to be referred to Dr Chien-Wen Liew at Orthopaedics 360\n3. Attend a consultation — ask every question you have\n4. Make a decision, in your own time\n\nIf you\'re in Adelaide and you\'ve been putting this off — let this be the year.\n\n📞 Referrals can be made by your GP to Orthopaedics 360 at Eastwood Private Hospital.\n🌐 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\nThis post contains general educational information only. Please consult your GP or specialist for advice tailored to your situation.', 'hashtags': '#NewYear2027 #JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #HipReplacementAdelaide #KneeReplacementAdelaide #AdelaideOrthopaedics #Orthopaedics360 #DrChienWenLiew', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2026-12-29-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Sunrise over Adelaide Hills, warm golden light on rolling hills and gum trees, clear sky, no people, hopeful and expansive landscape photography'},

{'id': 152, 'date': '2027-01-02', 'day': 'Saturday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Setting Surgical Goals for 2027 — A Clinical Reflection for GPs', 'caption': 'Setting surgical goals for 2027: a clinical reflection for GPs and referring doctors.\n\nAs the new year begins, it is worth taking a few minutes to consider the patients in your practice who might benefit from orthopaedic assessment in 2027 — and to think about what a productive year of arthroplasty referral looks like from a GP\'s perspective.\n\nWhat does a "well-timed" arthroplasty referral look like?\n\nThe ideal referral reaches me when:\n- The patient has had a reasonable trial of conservative management (typically 3–6 months of physiotherapy, appropriate analgesia, activity modification)\n- Functional limitation is documented — not just "knee pain" but "unable to walk more than 200m, unable to climb stairs without significant pain, not sleeping due to pain"\n- Relevant imaging is available — weight-bearing X-rays, ideally not more than 12–18 months old\n- Relevant comorbidities are listed — particularly diabetes control, cardiovascular status, medications\n- The patient\'s goals and expectations are noted\n\nAt this stage, an orthopaedic assessment does not commit anyone to surgery. It opens an informed conversation.\n\nTargets for 2027\n\nI would encourage GP colleagues to consider a structured review of patients:\n- On long-term NSAID or opioid scripts for joint pain\n- Who have attended more than three times in 12 months with hip or knee complaints\n- With documented moderate-to-severe OA on X-ray who have not been referred\n- With limited mobility who have been attributed to "just getting older" without specific assessment\n\nThese patients may be candidates for a conversation and referral that could meaningfully change their year — and their decade.\n\nThank you for everything you do in coordinating care around arthroplasty patients. I look forward to working with you in 2027.\n\n#GPReferral #Arthroplasty #TJR #SurgicalPlanning #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #NewYear2027', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2027-01-02-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Clean modern GP consultation desk with an open patient file, pen, and a stethoscope placed neatly, warm morning light, no people, professional medical practice photography'},

{'id': 153, 'date': '2027-01-04', 'day': 'Monday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'New Year Intention — This Year I Will (Considering Joint Replacement)', 'caption': '"This year, I will stop letting pain make my decisions for me."\n\nIt\'s January. The year is fresh. And if you\'ve been carrying hip or knee pain for months — or years — this might be the moment the thought finally becomes an action.\n\nYou don\'t have to be certain. You don\'t have to have all the answers. You just have to make one move: talk to your GP.\n\nWhat that looks like:\n→ Book a GP appointment this week\n→ Tell them honestly how much pain is affecting your life\n→ Ask for a referral to an orthopaedic surgeon\n→ See what your options are\n\nThat\'s it. One appointment, one conversation, one referral.\n\nYou\'ve been saying "eventually" long enough.\n\n2027 can be the year you actually do it.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au — link in bio\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.', 'hashtags': '#NewYear2027 #JointReplacement #HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #NewYearNewStart #HipReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew #ThisYearIWill', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2027-01-04-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Early morning light on a quiet suburban street, long shadows, a lone figure walking in the far distance away from camera, no recognisable features, peaceful and forward-looking lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 154, 'date': '2027-01-05', 'day': 'Tuesday', 'platform': 'LinkedIn', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Arthroplasty Trends to Watch in 2027 — Implant Technology, Robotics, and Rehabilitation', 'caption': 'Arthroplasty trends to watch in 2027: implant technology, robotics, and rehabilitation.\n\nAs we begin the new year, here are the developments I am watching most closely in hip and knee arthroplasty.\n\n1. Robotic-assisted surgery: outcome differentiation by patient phenotype\nThe next horizon in robotic arthroplasty is moving beyond population-level RCTs to understanding which patient subgroups benefit most. Early data suggests that patients with complex deformity, high BMI, or anatomical variants have the greatest benefit from robotic guidance. Expect more targeted indication guidelines in 2027.\n\n2. Smart implants and remote monitoring\nInstrumented implants capable of transmitting load and movement data remotely are moving from research settings toward early clinical adoption. The implications for detecting early loosening, PJI, and optimising rehabilitation protocols are significant. Regulatory pathways in Australia remain complex, but 2027 may see first-in-class commercial devices reach our market.\n\n3. Personalised rehabilitation via wearable technology\nConsumer-grade wearables (accelerometers, gyroscopes) are increasingly validated against clinical gait analysis. The ability to monitor recovery at home — step count, symmetry, range of motion — and deliver personalised physio adjustments via telehealth is a practical, near-term improvement that several Australian physiotherapy groups are piloting.\n\n4. GLP-1 receptor agonists and the changing surgical candidate pool\n2027 will be the first full year in which a substantial proportion of patients referred for arthroplasty will have been on GLP-1 therapy. Anaesthetic guidance on pre-operative cessation continues to evolve. The critical question — whether weight loss achieved via GLP-1 produces the same reduction in peri-operative risk as weight loss achieved by other means — is being studied but not yet answered.\n\n5. Patient-reported outcome measure integration\nThe shift from paper-based to fully digital PROM pathways (ePROM) is accelerating across Australian arthroplasty units. Routine pre- and post-operative electronic collection will become the standard of care in most private hospitals in the next 2–3 years.\n\n6. Periprosthetic joint infection: improved diagnostics, evolving treatment\nAlpha-defensin and other synovial biomarkers are now commercially available and increasingly used in the evaluation of painful TJR. The IDSA and British Orthopaedic Association are both expected to update PJI management guidelines in 2027 with more granular DAIR candidacy criteria.\n\nA year of incremental but meaningful progress ahead.\n\n#Arthroplasty #JointReplacement #Robotics #SmartImplants #GLP1 #PJI #AdelaideOrthopaedics #MedEd #Orthopaedics360 #Trends2027', 'hashtags': '', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/orthopaedics-in-south-australia/', 'image_file': '2027-01-05-linkedin.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Futuristic clean white robotic surgical arm in a modern operating room, dramatic directional lighting, no people, advanced medical technology photography'},

{'id': 155, 'date': '2027-01-06', 'day': 'Wednesday', 'platform': 'Instagram', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Summer Check-In — How Joint Replacement Patients Are Going 6 Months Post-Op', 'caption': 'For patients who had hip or knee replacement around July last year — you\'re now at approximately 6 months post-op. Here\'s a check-in on what that usually looks like. ☀️\n\n🦵 6 months after knee replacement:\nMost patients at this stage have returned to everyday activities — walking, driving, shopping, light gardening — with significantly less pain than before surgery. The knee is still maturing: some patients notice mild stiffness in the morning, or aching after a big day. This is normal and continues to improve up to 12 months and beyond. Range of motion is usually close to its final level, though gentle stretching and cycling continue to help.\n\n🦴 6 months after hip replacement:\nMost anterior approach hip replacement patients are fully weight-bearing, driving, and functionally independent well before this stage. At 6 months, the conversation shifts to return to more demanding activities — golf, longer walks, cycling, holidays. Most hip precautions are lifted by 3 months. The 6-month point is often when patients start to forget the hip replacement is even there.\n\n📋 What to do at 6 months:\n- Attend any scheduled orthopaedic follow-up\n- Continue physiotherapy if still recommended\n- Report any new pain, swelling, or mechanical symptoms promptly — don\'t assume it\'s "just normal"\n- Resume any activities your surgeon has cleared\n\n💬 6 months is not the finish line — it\'s the beginning of enjoying the result.\n\n📍 Dr Chien-Wen Liew | Hip & Knee Replacement Surgeon, Adelaide\n🔗 drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n⚠️ General educational information only. Individual treatment decisions should be made in consultation with your own medical team.', 'hashtags': '#HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #6MonthsPostOp #JointReplacement #AdelaideOrthopaedicSurgeon #Orthopaedics360 #RecoveryUpdate #HipReplacementAdelaide #DrChienWenLiew #LifeAfterSurgery', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/knee-replacement-recovery/', 'image_file': '2027-01-06-instagram.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Active adults in their 60s walking along an Adelaide beachside path in summer, figures small and relaxed, soft morning light on water, no faces clearly visible, aspirational active lifestyle photography'},

{'id': 156, 'date': '2027-01-06', 'day': 'Wednesday', 'platform': 'Facebook', 'li_audience': '', 'format': 'Post', 'topic': 'Hip and Knee Replacement Consultations in 2027 — How to Get Started', 'caption': "Ready to do something about your hip or knee pain in 2027? Here's everything you need to know to get started.\n\nWho is Dr Chien-Wen Liew?\n\nDr Liew is an orthopaedic surgeon based in Adelaide, specialising in hip and knee replacement surgery at Eastwood Private Hospital. He uses the anterior (front) approach for hip replacements — a muscle-sparing technique associated with faster early recovery — and offers the full range of knee replacement options including total, partial, and complex revision surgery.\n\nHow do I get a consultation?\n\nStep 1: See your GP and ask for a referral. Mention you'd like to see Dr Chien-Wen Liew at Orthopaedics 360.\n\nStep 2: Your GP sends the referral. Our team will contact you within 2 business days to arrange an appointment.\n\nStep 3: Attend your consultation. Bring any X-rays or imaging you have. Bring your questions — there are no silly ones.\n\nWhat if I'm not sure I need surgery?\n\nThat's completely fine. A consultation is just an assessment. It helps you understand your options — including non-surgical ones — and make a fully informed decision in your own time.\n\nHow long is the wait?\n\nPrivate patients are typically seen within 1–3 weeks of referral. January often has good availability.\n\n🌐 More information at drchienwenliew.com.au\n\n📍 Orthopaedics 360 | Eastwood Private Hospital, Adelaide\n\nThis post contains general educational information only. Please consult your GP or specialist for advice tailored to your situation.", 'hashtags': '#HipReplacement #KneeReplacement #HipReplacementAdelaide #KneeReplacementAdelaide #AdelaideOrthopaedics #Orthopaedics360 #DrChienWenLiew #JointReplacement #OrthopedicSurgeonAdelaide', 'website_link': 'https://drchienwenliew.com.au/blog/preparing-for-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery/', 'image_file': '2027-01-06-facebook.jpg', 'nanobanana_prompt': 'Premium private hospital main entrance facade, glass and timber architecture, manicured garden approach, clear blue sky, no people, architectural exterior photography'},

